86
00:04:59.880 --> 00:05:03.660
There's more than 50,000 patients a year in the US alone that are

87
00:05:05.100 --> 00:05:09.050
suffering from this disease. And up to 90% of those patients have

88
00:05:09.080 --> 00:05:12.760
a mutation that causes loss of function of a protein called VHL.

89
00:05:13.560 --> 00:05:17.490
And so what you can see in this middle slide here is that

90
00:05:17.520 --> 00:05:21.100
you can have a transforming event whereby VHL loss

91
00:05:21.640 --> 00:05:24.900
stabilizes hypoxia-inducible factor signaling.

92
00:05:24.980 --> 00:05:28.950
So, rather than this being an induced phenomenon, now you have

93
00:05:28.980 --> 00:05:30.800
constitutive expression of the HIFs,

94
00:05:31.980 --> 00:05:35.880
and this drives a transcriptional program, in which case a number of

95
00:05:35.920 --> 00:05:39.400
proteins, including, for example, VEGF, are expressed

96
00:05:39.440 --> 00:05:42.580
aberrantly, and this leads to transformation of these cells.

97
00:05:42.620 --> 00:05:46.080
And so our therapeutic hypothesis is that if we

98
00:05:46.140 --> 00:05:49.740
could address and reverse this constitutive HIF signaling,

99
00:05:50.260 --> 00:05:50.560
you would

100
00:05:52.740 --> 00:05:56.320
capture anti-tumor biology that normal cells would not be

101
00:05:56.380 --> 00:06:00.210
dependent upon. Because in a normal context, cells are not

102
00:06:00.240 --> 00:06:03.552
expressing these proteins.And so if we just zoom in

103
00:06:04.092 --> 00:06:06.312
now on this complex here at the middle,

104
00:06:07.332 --> 00:06:11.252
what you can see is that you have downstream of VHL now

105
00:06:11.292 --> 00:06:14.932
you have this constitutive expression of HIF-1 alpha and HIF-2

106
00:06:14.992 --> 00:06:15.312
alpha.

107
00:06:16.212 --> 00:06:20.062
And these proteins now, before they can start their transcriptional

108
00:06:20.172 --> 00:06:23.632
program, they have to dimerize with this protein called Arnt.

109
00:06:24.112 --> 00:06:25.992
And this is the obligate dimer partner.

110
00:06:26.052 --> 00:06:29.772
These HIF-1 alpha and HIF-2 alpha have no transcriptional activity

111
00:06:29.852 --> 00:06:32.872
without binding to the adaptor proteins.

112
00:06:33.492 --> 00:06:35.152
And so you can imagine

113
00:06:35.972 --> 00:06:39.832
that this is now the key node. It's really the critical feature at the heart of

114
00:06:39.892 --> 00:06:42.992
this pathway. And this is extremely robust biology.

115
00:06:43.292 --> 00:06:46.892
There was just the Nobel Prize awarded to some of the

116
00:06:47.252 --> 00:06:51.172
authors listed in these articles in the bottom corner.

117
00:06:51.832 --> 00:06:55.822
But you can also see that this pathway is now extremely well-validated

118
00:06:55.952 --> 00:06:56.432
clinically.

119
00:06:57.792 --> 00:06:57.992
So

120
00:06:58.832 --> 00:07:02.512
there are a number of approvals for VEGF receptor tyrosine

121
00:07:02.532 --> 00:07:05.792
kinase inhibitors. That includes lenvatinib, cabozantinib.

122
00:07:06.212 --> 00:07:09.852
But more recently, there's also been approvals for these HIF-2 alpha

123
00:07:09.932 --> 00:07:13.892
inhibitors such as belzutifan. And belzutifan,

124
00:07:13.972 --> 00:07:17.612
for example, binds to HIF-2 alpha and disrupts the dimer with

125
00:07:17.672 --> 00:07:21.532
Arnt. And so they're able to block the activity of

126
00:07:21.592 --> 00:07:25.512
this protein. But of course, as we look at this pathway, we're interested now

127
00:07:25.552 --> 00:07:29.252
in the broader effect of this pan-HIF mechanism whereby you would shut down the

128
00:07:29.292 --> 00:07:30.152
entire pathway.

129
00:07:31.592 --> 00:07:35.152
Now, the biology, as I said, is extremely robust, but of course, we wanted to get

130
00:07:35.232 --> 00:07:38.272
