483
00:28:17.380 --> 00:28:21.240
platform, which is a novel TCE format that preferentially engages

484
00:28:21.280 --> 00:28:25.140
the CD8 T-cells over the CD4s, and that allows

485
00:28:25.180 --> 00:28:28.620
us to reduce cytokine release while preserving cytotoxic

486
00:28:28.680 --> 00:28:29.340
responses.

487
00:28:30.840 --> 00:28:33.900
So I'll start by telling you a bit about why we're so excited about STEAP2.

488
00:28:34.679 --> 00:28:38.160
STEAP2 is a metalloreductase with a critical role in prostate

489
00:28:38.180 --> 00:28:42.040
biology, but the key attributes of STEAP2 that really make

490
00:28:42.140 --> 00:28:46.009
it an ideal TCE target is that it is expressed on

491
00:28:46.040 --> 00:28:49.700
the surface of prostate adenocarcinoma cells at a higher

492
00:28:49.760 --> 00:28:53.580
level than on normal prostate tissue and at a much higher level than on any

493
00:28:53.660 --> 00:28:54.460
other tissue type.

494
00:28:55.560 --> 00:28:59.180
So when we look at this normal tissue expression, it

495
00:28:59.240 --> 00:29:02.960
really suggests a low risk of on-target, off-tumor

496
00:29:03.000 --> 00:29:03.640
toxicity.

497
00:29:04.760 --> 00:29:08.220
When we compare that to PSMA, which is a clinically validated

498
00:29:08.640 --> 00:29:12.400
prostate TAA, we see a much cleaner normal tissue expression

499
00:29:12.480 --> 00:29:16.360
profile for STEAP2 with reduced surface expression on several

500
00:29:16.380 --> 00:29:19.300
organs, including ones that have been shown to be

501
00:29:19.340 --> 00:29:20.900
involved in

502
00:29:22.300 --> 00:29:25.960
toxicities induced by PSMA-targeted therapeutics, such as the

503
00:29:26.000 --> 00:29:27.680
intestine and the salivary gland.

504
00:29:29.100 --> 00:29:32.740
When we then look at the prevalence of STEAP2 on lesions from

505
00:29:32.800 --> 00:29:36.660
metastatic castration-resistant prostate cancer, what we can see

506
00:29:36.720 --> 00:29:39.980
is that virtually all lesions have most cells expressing

507
00:29:40.020 --> 00:29:42.680
STEAP2. That's in the red and the orange bars.

508
00:29:43.820 --> 00:29:47.640
And this type of expression profile is also conserved across all

509
00:29:47.650 --> 00:29:51.440
stages of the disease and all metastatic sites.

510
00:29:51.500 --> 00:29:55.450
If we compare now staying those lesions for PSMA, what you

511
00:29:55.460 --> 00:29:59.300
can see is there's a much larger proportion of lesions where very few cells express

512
00:29:59.360 --> 00:30:00.900
PSMA, shown in the blue.

513
00:30:01.910 --> 00:30:05.880
And we know that the density and the homogeneity of TAA expression

514
00:30:06.340 --> 00:30:09.210
is a key determinant of TCE anti-tumor activity.

515
00:30:09.680 --> 00:30:13.390
So this expression profile of STEAP2 is really very promising and

516
00:30:13.420 --> 00:30:16.420
aligns quite closely to what we'd want from an ideal TCE

517
00:30:16.480 --> 00:30:20.248
target.So to

518
00:30:20.268 --> 00:30:23.777
address the second challenge that I was mentioning, which is the incidence of

519
00:30:23.868 --> 00:30:25.808
high-grade cytokine release syndrome.

520
00:30:26.528 --> 00:30:29.928
Here we're really looking to use this CD8 guided format.

521
00:30:30.458 --> 00:30:33.448
And why do we think that CD8 guidance could help with this?

522
00:30:34.128 --> 00:30:37.688
Well, here we're really looking at a differential role between CD8 T cells and

523
00:30:37.748 --> 00:30:41.287
CD4 T cells in the response to a conventional, here

524
00:30:41.368 --> 00:30:45.348
non-CD8 guided T cell engager. And what you can see is that

525
00:30:45.388 --> 00:30:49.208
when we culture tumor cells with either purified CD8

526
00:30:49.288 --> 00:30:53.168
or CD4 T cells, they have a very different response, with the

527
00:30:53.208 --> 00:30:57.068
purified CD8s being more cytotoxic but producing

528
00:30:57.128 --> 00:30:59.778
less cytokines than the purified CD4s.

529
00:31:00.948 --> 00:31:04.768
Similarly, if we look in vivo in our humanized mouse models, if we

530
00:31:04.788 --> 00:31:08.658
deplete the CD4 T cells, we see a significant reduction in the amount of

531
00:31:08.748 --> 00:31:11.348
cytokine release that we get after TCE treatment.

532
00:31:11.957 --> 00:31:14.828
That doesn't happen if we deplete the CD8 T cells.

533
00:31:14.868 --> 00:31:18.128
So these data really support the hypothesis of

534
00:31:18.188 --> 00:31:21.828
incorporating a CD8 bias into our TCEs to really

535
00:31:21.908 --> 00:31:25.228
capitalize on that cytotoxic activity of the CD8 T

536
00:31:25.247 --> 00:31:29.228
cells and reduce the cytokine producing activity of the

537
00:31:29.268 --> 00:31:30.368
CD4 T cells.

538
00:31:31.768 --> 00:31:33.788
So what does a TCE that can do that look like?

539
00:31:34.608 --> 00:31:38.548
Well, here's a schematic of AZD8359, and as you can

540
00:31:38.648 --> 00:31:42.148
see it has bivalent targeting of the STIP2

541
00:31:42.348 --> 00:31:42.788
TAA,

542
00:31:43.748 --> 00:31:47.588
which was selected based on its expression profile to deliver both potent

543
00:31:47.688 --> 00:31:51.468
antitumor activity and a reduced risk of on-target off-tumor

544
00:31:51.488 --> 00:31:52.228
toxicity.

545
00:31:53.148 --> 00:31:57.048
It also incorporates the CD8 binding domain, which is our guiding arm

546
00:31:57.408 --> 00:32:01.208
that biases the activity towards the CD8 T cells, which are the main

547
00:32:01.308 --> 00:32:05.208
cytotoxic cell type, and away from the CD4s, which are the

548
00:32:05.268 --> 00:32:09.128
main cytokine producing cell type, and they've been identified as key drivers

549
00:32:09.188 --> 00:32:09.888
of CRS.

550
00:32:11.008 --> 00:32:14.628
And finally, it contains a TCR agonist domain to

551
00:32:14.728 --> 00:32:16.448
stimulate the T cells.

552
00:32:18.428 --> 00:32:21.288
So in the next part of my talk, I'll show you a bit of the data we've generated

553
00:32:21.768 --> 00:32:25.748
that underpins the potential for AZD8359

554
00:32:25.948 --> 00:32:27.648
to transform outcomes in the clinic.

555
00:32:28.407 --> 00:32:32.028
So we initially sought to confirm that the design of the TCE was

556
00:32:32.048 --> 00:32:33.738
delivering the anticipated activity.

557
00:32:34.368 --> 00:32:38.008
So we used a STIP2 knockout cell line, to

558
00:32:38.028 --> 00:32:41.868
confirm that the cytotoxicity we're seeing in vitro is indeed STIP2

559
00:32:41.888 --> 00:32:45.648
dependent. And then we generated some tool reagents where

560
00:32:45.708 --> 00:32:49.588
we took out either the TCR engaging arm or the CD8

561
00:32:49.668 --> 00:32:52.968
binding arm. And what we saw is that the

562
00:32:53.028 --> 00:32:56.828
cytotoxicity is entirely dependent on the binding to the TCR.

563
00:32:57.788 --> 00:33:01.468
But actually you can get killing in the absence of the CD8 binding arm,

564
00:33:01.668 --> 00:33:05.528
but that arm does confer a much increased potency to the

565
00:33:05.568 --> 00:33:09.548
final molecule. When we then looked at the activation of the

566
00:33:09.588 --> 00:33:13.477
T cells at the end of these assays, what we could see is that with a conventional

567
00:33:13.728 --> 00:33:17.688
non-CD8-guided TCE, both CD8s and CD4 T cells are

568
00:33:17.768 --> 00:33:18.688
equally activated.

569
00:33:19.948 --> 00:33:22.648
If we treat instead with our CD8 guided TCE,

570
00:33:22.908 --> 00:33:26.068
AZD8359, what we saw was the

571
00:33:26.748 --> 00:33:30.668
anticipated increased activation of CD8 T cells over

572
00:33:30.708 --> 00:33:31.808
CD4 T cells.

573
00:33:33.668 --> 00:33:37.228
And we could also see that with another methodology, so looking at the behavior of

574
00:33:37.268 --> 00:33:39.308
the T cells using live cell imaging.

575
00:33:40.028 --> 00:33:43.908
And what you can see in this video is it allows us to visualize the

576
00:33:44.468 --> 00:33:48.228
CD8 T cell in blue contacting the green tumor cell,

577
00:33:48.608 --> 00:33:52.088
and you can see that they're both bound by the TCE that's shown in purple.

578
00:33:53.008 --> 00:33:56.768
And with these videos, we can quantify the amount of

579
00:33:56.888 --> 00:33:59.808
time that a T cell is in contact with a tumor cell.

580
00:34:01.648 --> 00:34:05.388
And what we saw is that if you treat these cells with a

581
00:34:05.448 --> 00:34:07.908
conventional 2+1 TCE,

582
00:34:08.708 --> 00:34:12.629
both the CD4s and the CD8s equally increase the

583
00:34:12.669 --> 00:34:16.629
amount of time they spend in contact with a tumor cell, likely due to the

584
00:34:16.688 --> 00:34:20.629
formation of immune synapses. However, when we treated

585
00:34:20.669 --> 00:34:24.328
with our CD8 guided TCE, AZD8359,

586
00:34:24.948 --> 00:34:28.928
only the CD8 T cells increased that contact time with the tumor cells

587
00:34:29.328 --> 00:34:33.188
forming those immune synapses. And you can hopefully see that in this

588
00:34:33.228 --> 00:34:37.089
video where the red CD4 T cells are very mobile, but the

589
00:34:37.109 --> 00:34:41.069
blue CD8 T cells are much more often stuck in the vicinity of a tumor,

590
00:34:41.848 --> 00:34:43.508
likely in an immune synapse.

591
00:34:44.528 --> 00:34:47.968
So we're really excited to see this, and we went on to evaluate

592
00:34:48.109 --> 00:34:51.548
AZD8359 in in vivo humanized mouse models.

593
00:34:52.258 --> 00:34:56.028
And what we saw here was very potent activity here in a flank tumor model.

594
00:34:56.948 --> 00:35:00.568
And importantly, that activity was STIP2 dependent, so we saw no

595
00:35:00.608 --> 00:35:03.848
effect of an untargeted isotype control TCE.

596
00:35:05.068 --> 00:35:08.818
But we then sought to increase the physiological relevance of this animal model to

597
00:35:08.828 --> 00:35:12.788
the bone metastasis setting, which is very frequent in late stage

598
00:35:12.868 --> 00:35:16.568
prostate cancer. So we developed an intratubal tumor

599
00:35:16.628 --> 00:35:16.888
model,

600
00:35:17.788 --> 00:35:21.688
and we were able to demonstrate that in that model, AZD8359

601
00:35:21.728 --> 00:35:25.027
could completely clear the tumors in these mice.

602
00:35:25.948 --> 00:35:28.348
So very potent activity we're seeing in vivo.

603
00:35:29.128 --> 00:35:33.108
This was all very promising data, but really it's the next data set that

604
00:35:33.148 --> 00:35:35.008
got us very excited about this molecule.

605
00:35:35.808 --> 00:35:39.228
And that's that we can see in vitro and in vivo that

606
00:35:39.288 --> 00:35:42.808
AZD8359 has a wider preclinical

607
00:35:42.928 --> 00:35:46.768
therapeutic index compared to a conventional non-CD8 guided

608
00:35:46.828 --> 00:35:47.248
TCE.

609
00:35:48.248 --> 00:35:52.048
So here you can see in vitro that the window between the cytotoxic

610
00:35:52.108 --> 00:35:55.648
effect and the cytokine release, so the area shaded in purple,

611
00:35:56.028 --> 00:36:00.008
is much bigger for AZD8359 compared to a standard

612
00:36:00.628 --> 00:36:01.648
2+1 TCE.

613
00:36:02.688 --> 00:36:06.428
And when we look in vivo in our humanized mouse models, if we have dose

614
00:36:06.488 --> 00:36:09.828
levels that give the same amount of antitumor activity,

615
00:36:10.608 --> 00:36:14.308
AZD8359 leads to significantly less cytokine

616
00:36:14.328 --> 00:36:17.958
release in these animals after treatment compared to a conventional

617
00:36:18.028 --> 00:36:21.976
non-CD8 guided TCE.So this data really supports

618
00:36:22.516 --> 00:36:25.916
the hypothesis that CD8 guidance can deliver potent

619
00:36:26.036 --> 00:36:29.996
antitumor activity, but with reduced cytokine release and

620
00:36:30.016 --> 00:36:33.216
therefore potentially a reduced risk of CRS in the clinic.

621
00:36:35.256 --> 00:36:39.156
So for the final part of my talk, I'd just like to broaden the view a bit more

622
00:36:39.276 --> 00:36:41.556
just beyond AZD8359.

623
00:36:42.536 --> 00:36:46.476
We know that the format of a TCE is critical in how it

624
00:36:46.576 --> 00:36:50.516
binds to its multiple targets, how it brings the tumor cell and the T cell

625
00:36:50.576 --> 00:36:53.656
together to form an effective immune synapse.

626
00:36:53.696 --> 00:36:56.916
So we've been exploring the impact of a TCE

627
00:36:56.976 --> 00:37:00.956
format on how effectively we can redirect CD8 T cells

628
00:37:01.016 --> 00:37:02.096
to kill tumor cells.

629
00:37:03.256 --> 00:37:07.156
And here what you can see are two molecules that we've characterized preclinically

630
00:37:07.216 --> 00:37:10.796
to target STING2, AZD6621 and

631
00:37:10.916 --> 00:37:14.656
AZD8359, and they differ both in their stimulation domain

632
00:37:15.076 --> 00:37:18.456
but also in their geometry, with the CD8 binding arm being in the

633
00:37:18.556 --> 00:37:21.236
hinge of the titan format that's used for

634
00:37:21.276 --> 00:37:22.876
AZD8359.

635
00:37:24.816 --> 00:37:28.536
What was really encouraging though, is we found that multiple formats can deliver

636
00:37:28.556 --> 00:37:32.376
the CD8 guidance. So when we put these two molecules into our

637
00:37:32.396 --> 00:37:35.396
preclinical assays, they look extremely similar.

638
00:37:36.336 --> 00:37:40.196
Both of them are able to deliver a similarly improved

639
00:37:40.256 --> 00:37:43.386
in vitro therapeutic index compared to a conventional

640
00:37:43.656 --> 00:37:45.076
non-CD8-guided TCE.

641
00:37:45.896 --> 00:37:49.336
And when they're put into in vivo assays at matched

642
00:37:49.416 --> 00:37:52.776
efficacious dose levels, both of those molecules are able to

643
00:37:52.836 --> 00:37:55.856
significantly reduce the cytokine release seen in those animals.

644
00:37:56.576 --> 00:38:00.116
So really supporting the hypothesis that both of these formats

645
00:38:00.536 --> 00:38:04.316
could deliver optimal CD8 guidance preclinically, and so they

646
00:38:04.376 --> 00:38:08.156
both represent two promising shots on goal for our

647
00:38:08.456 --> 00:38:12.156
pursuit of a TCE with a wider therapeutic index in

648
00:38:12.196 --> 00:38:14.896
metastatic castration-resistant prostate cancer.

649
00:38:17.556 --> 00:38:21.536
So really, we are doubling down on next generation

650
00:38:21.816 --> 00:38:25.776
STING2 targeted CD8-guided TCEs to

651
00:38:25.856 --> 00:38:29.476
help unlock the full potential of TCEs in prostate cancer.

652
00:38:30.696 --> 00:38:32.496
Why do we think this approach is so promising?

653
00:38:33.236 --> 00:38:37.136
Because we're tackling the two challenges that are emerging from the clinical

654
00:38:37.216 --> 00:38:40.976
learnings with TCEs, which are firstly, the selection of the optimal

655
00:38:41.336 --> 00:38:44.525
TAA, and here we think that with STING2,

656
00:38:45.216 --> 00:38:49.166
we've really found an ideal target showing high homogeneous

657
00:38:49.256 --> 00:38:52.656
tumor cell expression across all stages of prostate adenocarcinoma

658
00:38:53.216 --> 00:38:56.876
and having limited normal tissue expression to reduce the risk

659
00:38:57.076 --> 00:38:59.016
of on-target, off-tumor toxicity.

660
00:38:59.876 --> 00:39:03.556
And secondly, mitigating the risk of cytokine release syndrome

661
00:39:03.856 --> 00:39:07.776
with a novel CD8-guided format that we have shown to

662
00:39:07.876 --> 00:39:11.736
deliver preferential CD8 T cell engagement, which leads

663
00:39:11.816 --> 00:39:15.576
to potent antitumor activity, but with reduced cytokine

664
00:39:15.616 --> 00:39:15.996
release.

665
00:39:17.616 --> 00:39:21.336
So with that, I'd like to thank the entire AZD8359 team and all of the

666
00:39:21.376 --> 00:39:24.216
supporting team members, and thank you so much for your attention.

667
00:39:24.516 --> 00:39:25.696
Happy to take any questions.

668
00:39:34.596 --> 00:39:37.296
Please go to the microphone for questions. Let's start in the middle.

669
00:39:38.136 --> 00:39:41.696
Hello. Excellent talk. I'm Tiong San from InnoVent. Two quick questions.

